CORR. Log entry : Payment Classifications : Maine still provides state supplement payments to individuals living in Adult Family Care Homes (AFCH). This payment level is the same as Cost Reimbursed Boarding Homes (CRBH) so we added this to the living arrangement description.
Maine has not eliminated payments. SPA 18-004 included two classifications for Living in a Medical Facility; one was labelled “Living in Med. Fac. Or ICF would receive Supplement Payment if outside facility”. The state supplement amount and income standard is this classification is the same as an individual in an independent living classification, and was left out of this submission. We have added this back in as “Living in Medical Institution <90 days”. 
Both the calculations for living in household of another and living in a medical institutions seem to match up with the calculations in 18-004. 
•	“Living in household of another” includes individuals who receive a reduced SSI payment and receive a $8/$12 State Supp. The net income standard would be 2/3rds the SSI standard plus the state supplement. Does this need to be listed the below in “Other payment classification” section instead?
•	“Living in Medical Facility” includes individuals who are receiving the reduced SSI payment ($30) due to being in a facility for 30+ days. 
The additional information section has been corrected.

Log entry : Payment Classifications : During the 15-day call on 12/17/19, Maine confirmed it still offers its optional state supplement payment to individuals living in an adult day care home (see eligibility policy manual, April 2019). Please add this payment classification to Section D.1. of the "Optional State Supplement Beneficiaries" Reviewable Unit. The State also confirmed that it no longer pays a supplement to individuals residing in a particular arrangement that was included in SPA ME 18-004. Please provide more detail about which payment classification/living arrangement no longer receives the state supplement and the rationale behind this decision.
Based on the information provided in the "Additional Information" section of the RU, please update these payment classifications' income standards: "living in household of another" (to $791 for individuals and $1,187 for couples) and "living in medical institution" (to $823 for individuals and $1,195 for couples). The State should also update the "independent living" couple's maximum state supplement payment listed in the "Additional Information" section to $15.

CORR. Log entry : VA SPA 19-0016 : The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) has received your submission of Virginia SPA 19-0016, Cover Virginia and Eligibility Determinations and we have the following comments and requests:
1.	The single state agency should upload a new organizational chart in A.3. The state appears to have changed the organizational structure of its single state agency since it last submitted an organizational chart dated 8.23.18. On the single state agency’s website, there is an organizational chart dated 10.28.19, which incorporates changes to the agency’s organization (http://www.dmas.virginia.gov/files/links/1113/Agency%20Org%20Structure.pdf). 
The state should upload an updated organizational chart (without leadership names). 
2.	The state should also revise the descriptions A.2.c. and A.2.f. 
In A.2.C., the state refers to the “Integrated Care and Behavioral Health Division,” the updated organizational chart includes an “Integrated Care Division” and a “Behavioral Health Division.” The state should correct its discussion to reflect that these are two separate divisions and ensure that the description of their functions are still accurate. 
In A.2.C., the state refers to the “Long-Term Care Division,” no such division exists on the state’s organizational chart. The state should include the name of the correct division and/or identify whether the long-term care activities describe are accomplished at the “unit” level. 
In A.2.F., the state refers to the “Fiscal and Purchases Division,” no such division exist on the agency’s organizational chart. The state should correct the name of the division and its functions as appropriate. 
3.	The state should ensure that descriptions contained in A.2.a-h continue to accurately reflect the function of the divisions within the single state agency and revise where appropriate.
Would you please provide this additional information via MACPro by 01/10/2020? Please let us know if you have any questions about this request. 
Thank you for your assistance.

CORR. Log entry : Initial CMS Comments and Guidance for AZ : Arizona's September 30, 2019 census disregard SPA submission was deemed approved on December 29, 2019 with an effective date of July 1, 2019. The approval letter was sent to the state on January 9, 2020.
CMS will continue to process this December 17, 2019 MACPro submission to incorporate the changes approved in the September 30, 2019 submission into MACPro and so that we have the additional baseline eligibility information required by MACPro. The MACPro submission will have an effective date of October 1, 2019.
While the MACPro version will be substantially similar to the paper version, there will be some structural differences. Specifically-the paper-based version lays out on one page the census disregard and the groups to which it applies; in MACPro, however, the state will need to spell out in its non-MAGI methodologies “Reviewable Unit” (RU) certain financial policies that the state applies to non-MAGI groups; additionally the state must select the specific eligibility groups to which the census income disregard will be applied and submit corresponding RUs.
In addition to the RU that the state already submitted, “Eligibility Determinations of Individuals Age 65 or Older or Who Have Blindness or a Disability”, the state will need to complete the following RUs:
1) Non-MAGI Methodologies- which has a statement about whether the state has any disregards;
2) Mandatory Eligibility Groups (select the groups that the census disregards will be applicable to);
a. For each eligibility group selected- say what disregards apply to income;
b. For each eligibility group selected- say what disregards apply to resources;
3) Optional Eligibility Groups (select the ones that census disregard will be applicable to)
a. For each eligibility group selected- say what disregards apply to income;
b. For each eligibility group selected- say what disregards apply to resources;
MACPro is structured in such a way that some information is embedded within other Reviewable Units. These resources on the Medicaid.gov MACPro website (https://www.medicaid.gov/state-resource-center/medicaid-and-chip-program-portal/medicaid-and-chip-program-portal.html#MACPro) may be helpful: MACPro Medicaid State Plan Reference Document for State Users, Introductory Guide to Creating Medicaid Eligibility SPAs in MACPro, and Crosswalk from Paper-based Plan to MACPro and MMDL. Additionally, we have attached the census slidedeck we shared with Eligibility Technical Advisory Group participants in July 2019 (see slides 6-7 for screenshots).
Below is a more step-by-step set of directions for the submissions described above (refer to the "Introductory Guide" for additional information):
1. Within the Submission--Summary Reviewable Unit, Eligibility Section
a. Income/Resource Methodologies
 i. Non-MAGI Methodologies
b. Mandatory Eligibility Groups
c. Optional Eligibility Groups
2. Within the Mandatory Eligibility Groups Reviewable Unit
a. Qualified Medicare Beneficiaries (add applicable disregards to RU)
b. Specified Low-Income Medicare Beneficiaries (add applicable disregards to RU)
c. Qualifying Individuals (add applicable disregards to RU)
3. Within the Optional Eligibility Groups Reviewable Unit
a. Individuals Eligible For but Not Receiving Cash Assistance (add applicable disregards to RU)
b. Ticket to Work Basic (add applicable disregards to RU)
c. Ticket to Work Medically Improved (add applicable disregards to RU)
CMS is available for (and recommends) another technical assistance call as Arizona revises its MACPro submission.

Log entry : Individuals Receiving Home and Community-Based Waiver Services under Institutional Rules : For the Individuals Receiving Home and Community-Based Waiver Services under Institutional Rules RU, the state should confirm whether it intends for the Census income disregard to be targeted to the 217 group when the disregard does not apply to the principal eligibility group. In determining eligibility for this particular eligibility group, a state hypothetically assumes an applicant’s institutionalization and then scans the eligibility groups covered under its state plan to identify whether, assuming the individual’s institutional status, the individual would be eligible for Medicaid. These other eligibility groups are sometimes referred to as the "principal groups," and states select in their 1915(c) waivers which groups covered under their state plans to have serve as the principal groups. Income or resource disregards that apply to a principal group are automatically applied in determining eligibility for the 217 group. Thus, the income disregards to be inputted in this reviewable unit should only be those that South Dakota wants to target to the 217 group.
If the state does not intend to target this disregard only to the 217 group, this RU may be removed from the package.

CORR. Log entry : Initial CMS Comments and Guidance for AZ : Arizona's September 30, 2019 census disregard SPA submission was deemed approved on December 29, 2019 with an effective date of July 1, 2019. The approval letter was sent to the state on January 9, 2020.
CMS will continue to process this December 17, 2019 MACPro submission to incorporate the changes approved in the September 30, 2019 submission into MACPro and so that we have the additional baseline eligibility information required by MACPro. The MACPro submission will have an effective date of October 1, 2019.
While the MACPro version will be substantially similar to the paper version, there will be some structural differences. Specifically-the paper-based version lays out on one page the census disregard and the groups to which it applies; in MACPro, however, the state will need to spell out in its non-MAGI methodologies “Reviewable Unit” (RU) certain financial policies that the state applies to non-MAGI groups; additionally the state must select the specific eligibility groups to which the census income disregard will be applied and submit corresponding RUs.
In addition to the RU that the state already submitted, “Eligibility Determinations of Individuals Age 65 or Older or Who Have Blindness or a Disability”, the state will need to complete the following RUs:
1) Non-MAGI Methodologies- which has a statement about whether the state has any disregards;
2) Mandatory Eligibility Groups (select the groups that the census disregards will be applicable to);
a. For each eligibility group selected- say what disregards apply to income;
b. For each eligibility group selected- say what disregards apply to resources;
3) Optional Eligibility Groups (select the ones that census disregard will be applicable to)
a. For each eligibility group selected- say what disregards apply to income;
b. For each eligibility group selected- say what disregards apply to resources;
MACPro is structured in such a way that some information is embedded within other Reviewable Units. These resources on the Medicaid.gov MACPro website (https://www.medicaid.gov/state-resource-center/medicaid-and-chip-program-portal/medicaid-and-chip-program-portal.html#MACPro) may be helpful: MACPro Medicaid State Plan Reference Document for State Users, Introductory Guide to Creating Medicaid Eligibility SPAs in MACPro, and Crosswalk from Paper-based Plan to MACPro and MMDL. Additionally, we have attached the census slidedeck we shared with Eligibility Technical Advisory Group participants in July 2019 (see slides 6-7 for screenshots).
Below is a more step-by-step set of directions for the submissions described above (refer to the "Introductory Guide" for additional information):
1. Within the Submission--Summary Reviewable Unit, Eligibility Section
a. Income/Resource Methodologies
 i. Non-MAGI Methodologies
b. Mandatory Eligibility Groups
c. Optional Eligibility Groups
2. Within the Mandatory Eligibility Groups Reviewable Unit
a. Qualified Medicare Beneficiaries (add applicable disregards to RU)
b. Specified Low-Income Medicare Beneficiaries (add applicable disregards to RU)
c. Qualifying Individuals (add applicable disregards to RU)
3. Within the Optional Eligibility Groups Reviewable Unit
a. Individuals Eligible For but Not Receiving Cash Assistance (add applicable disregards to RU)
b. Ticket to Work Basic (add applicable disregards to RU)
c. Ticket to Work Medically Improved (add applicable disregards to RU)
CMS is available for (and recommends) another technical assistance call as Arizona revises its MACPro submission.
